Introduction¶

The information was obtained from the FBI's National Instant Criminal Background Check System. The NICS is used to determine whether a prospective buyer is qualified to purchase firearms or explosives. This system is used by gun shops to ensure that each customer does not have a criminal record or is otherwise ineligible to make a purchase. The data has been supplemented with state level data from census.gov

  • The NICS data is contained in a single sheet of an.xlsx file. It includes the number of firearm checks performed by month, state, and type
  • The U.S. census data is stored in a.csv file. At the state level, it contains a number of variables. Most variables have only one data point per state (2016), but a few have data for more than one year.

</ul>

Background check types included in the FBI gun data include "permit," "permit recheck," "handgun," "long gun," and "multiple" (purchasing more than one gun per background check). Each month and state has a data point that includes all of the variables mentioned above.

Questions to answer:

  1. What census data is most associated with high gun registration?

  2. Is there a correlation between ethnic group proportion and gun registration?

  3. Is there a seasonal pattern for firearm shopping?

  4. Which states have had the highest growth in gun registrations?

  5. What is the overall trend of gun purchases?

From the above operation performed, the following were oberserved:

  • The gun data has 27 columns and 12485 rows.
  • Gun Transactions contains a historic series of the number of transactions by weapon type and state. This dataset includes a data structure like this (per state and month): permits, permits recheck, handgun transactions, longgun transactions, other types of gun transactions, multiple types of gun transactions, and a detail for each gun type and transaction type: prepawn, rental, private sale, return to seller, etc..
  • The U.S. census data has 52 columns and 85 rows.
  • From the chart plotted, the variables in gun data are skewed to the right.
  • In the gun data, the data type of the "month" column was a string, which was supposed to be in datetime format.
  • The records from row 67 in the census data are irrelevant.
  • The data type for the census data are in string, whereas it is supposed to be integer.
  • All state columns in the census data seem to contain the same number of null values. Checking through the data, the irrelevant records are towards the end of the data.

Data Cleaning¶

The following steps are going to be taken in order to clean both the gun data and the census data.

  • In order to use the same format for numbers, we are going to change the data type of the columns "multiple" and "totals" in gun data to float.

  • Changing the month's data type format in gun data from string to datatime format.

  • Check if the states in the gun data and census data are the same. If not, remove the non-corresponding states.

    Conclusions¶

    According to the analysis, gun registration per capita was 0.39781331523550745 percent in 2010 and 0.677793404977627 percent in 2016. And this demonstrates that gun registration per capita has increased by roughly 70% since 2010.

    Furthermore, states such as Kentucky, California, Texas, Illinois, Pennsylvania, Ohio, and Tennessee maintained their position as the top states with high gun registration between 2010 and 2016. Furthermore, long guns are the most common type of firearm purchased by Americans over the years, followed by hand guns.

    Both datasets had a number of limitations and challenges. Missing data from the Census dataset, such as the five addressed colonies (District of Columbia, Guam, Mariana Islands, Puerto Rico, and Virgin Islands), may have contributed to the accuracy of the analysis. It would have been preferable if they had been included in order to properly calculate and verify the gun per capita figure. The datasets aren't standardized. Except for the columns "month", "state", "handgun", "long gun", "multiple", and "totals", almost all of the columns in the gun data appear to be almost entirely empty. Since the dataset is nearly empty, using an average or any other method becomes very difficult.

    The number of gun registrations has increased in every state except Utah, according to positive growth in gun registrations. Indiana has the highest growth rate of any state in the United States of America, at 250 percent. This could indicate that they are outliers, that there is increased reliance and trust in firearms, as well as decreased trust in police institutions, or that there are increased safety concerns for a variety of reasons.

    The line chart of gun sales vs. years 1997–2016 shows an increasing trend of gun purchases, with sharp increases in 2015 and 1998 and a decrease in 2016.

    The year-to-year comparisons of all states between 1999 and 2016 show that the number remains low in the summer and peaks in the winter. There was some inconsistency during the summer of 2016, which we need to investigate further.
